<HEADLINE>
<P>
A RAINBOW DISCOVERED AT CANYON; BOYS' BASKETBALL: COWBOYS GET A CHANCE TO 
SCHEDULE A TUNEUP FOR THE PLAYOFFS AFTER THEIR GAME AGAINST A TEAM FROM HAWAII 
IS CANCELED. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By BRYAN RODGERS, SPECIAL TO THE TIMES 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Canyon High boys' basketball Coach Greg Hayes may have lost an opportunity to 
play a game, but he hasn't lost his sense of humor. 
</P>
<P>
 Hayes attributes "a lack of communication" for a nonleague game against St. 
Louis High being canceled Wednesday when the team from Hawaii failed to show 
for a scheduled 7 p.m. start. 
</P>
<P>
 "At Canyon, we're used to having games canceled two ways," Hayes said. "When 
the roof in our gym leaks and earthquakes. This was easy." 
</P>
<P>
 The cancellation could turn out to be a blessing for the Cowboys. 
</P>
<P>
 With an odd number of teams in the Foothill League, Canyon's regular season 
ends almost a week before the playoffs begin. 
</P>
<P>
 The Southern Section permits teams to play a maximum of 20 games -- 
tournaments count for two games -- exclusive of playoffs. 
</P>
<P>
 Now the Cowboys will have the opportunity to schedule a nonleague game on the 
final week of the regular season in February.  
</P>
<P>
 "At the top of my Christmas list is someone for us to play after our regular 
season ends," Hayes said. 
</P>
<P>
 "I don't really want to head into the playoffs with a week between games." 
</P>
<P>
 Canyon thought a contract to play St. Louis had been secured last spring. 
</P>
<P>
 "We mailed them the paperwork and had everything set up," Hayes said. 
</P>
<P>
 Instead, St. Louis ventured into Orange County and played El Toro. 
</P>
<P>
 When Hayes contacted an assistant coach at the team's hotel, the coach claimed 
a representative of the team had called Canyon and canceled the game. 
</P>
<P>
 Meanwhile, fans, officials and players waited at Canyon High for the Hawaiian 
team to arrive. 
</P>
<P>
 "Once it got to be 6:30, we'd watch someone come through the door and think, 
'Hey, they look Hawaiian,' " Hayes said. 
</P>
<P>
 "You'd be amazed at how many Hawaiian-looking people live out here." 
</P>
</TEXT>
