</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
COUNTYWIDE FOCUS: AIRPORT SERVICE AND LEASES ARE PRAISED 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By CARLOS V. LOZANO 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 The department that oversees Ventura County's two airports has improved 
customer service and made significant progress in leasing vacant property, but 
can do more to improve airport management, according to a county audit released 
Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
 Airport Administrator Rodney Murphy, who took over the job in May, is credited 
with several improvements made at the Oxnard and Camarillo airports, says the 
report by Auditor-Controller Thomas O. Mahon. 
</P>
<P>
 For instance, customer service was greatly enhanced by expanding parking at 
the Oxnard Airport, establishing a noise complaint hot line and increasing 
involvement in annual public open houses at both airports. 
</P>
<P>
 The audit also praised the Department of Airports for its recent success in 
securing four long-term leases of vacant airport property. 
</P>
<P>
 But the report found several areas where improvements could be made. For 
example, the audit found that the department, which has an annual budget of 
$7.1 million, has been lax in collecting overdue lease payments and lacks a 
policy to charge airport tenants for hazardous waste cleanup costs. 
</P>
<P>
 More oversight is also needed in collecting various airport fees, monitoring 
capital improvement projects and submitting claims for state and federal 
grants, the audit found. In addition, the audit recommended that the department 
impose a $3 passenger fee -- already approved by the federal government -- to 
help pay for airport improvements.  
</P>
<P>
 Murphy could not be reached for comment, but Mahon said corrective action is 
already being taken in each of these areas. He said that improving airport 
management is vital to the county's efforts to lure additional businesses and 
industry to the area. 
</P>
<P>
 Oxnard Airport serves 92,000 passengers a year through three commercial 
airlines and is home to 120 privately owned aircraft. Camarillo Airport is a 
major provider of business transportation with 575 privately owned aircraft. 
CARLOS V. LOZANO 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column; Brief 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA122394-0133 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 110752 </DOCID>
<SOURCE>
<P>
 Los Angeles Times 
</P>
</SOURCE>
<DATE>
<P>
December 23, 1994, Friday, Ventura West Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Metro; Part B; Page 2; Column 5 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
181 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
COUNTYWIDE FOCUS: 5 AGENCIES GET GRANTS TO FIGHT HOMELESSNESS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By JAN STEVENS 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Five Ventura County agencies have been awarded $87,000 under a new state grant 
program aimed at encouraging local strategies to fight homelessness. 
</P>
<P>
 The state Department of Housing and Community Development gave Turning Point 
Foundation $40,000.Project Understanding and the Salvation Army received 
$13,580 each, while Lutheran Social Services received $10,000 and Catholic 
Charities/Ventura Mental Health received $9,840. 
</P>
<P>
 The state's new Emergency Housing and Assistance Program is part of a state 
strategy to move homeless people from shelters to self-support as soon as 
possible. Grant money is used for shelter operation and construction, rental 
assistance and counseling and training. 
</P>
<P>
 "The state is attempting to move beyond simply providing emergency shelter and 
to focus on helping the homeless help themselves through counseling, substance 
abuse treatment where necessary and job training," said state Housing Director 
Timothy L. Coyle. 
</P>
<P>
 State officials said they expect to award $6 million in homeless grants 
statewide during the current fiscal year. JAN STEVENS 
</P>
</TEXT>
