<HEADLINE>
<P>
COMMUNITY NEWS FOCUS: GARDEN GROVE; CITY OKS 51-UNIT HOUSING PROJECT FOR SENIOR 
CITIZENS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By BERT ELJERA 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 The City Council this week unanimously approved a proposed 51-unit seniors 
housing project on the northeast corner of Nelson Street and Acacia Parkway. 
</P>
<P>
 The housing project will be built on a vacant 1.6-acre lot that developer 
SWACO Partnership has acquired from the city in exchange for a slightly more 
than half of an acre of property south of Acacia Parkway and east of Nelson 
Street. 
</P>
<P>
 The half-acre parcel currently has a 12-unit apartment, but city officials 
plan to tear down the building and develop the property for commercial 
purposes. Tenants in the 12-unit apartment are expected to move to the housing 
project once it is completed, officials said. 
</P>
<P>
 "This is a nice Christmas present," said Art Schatzeder, 76, a retired Cypress 
city engineer, who is developing the project with his partner, Telesforo 
Alvarez, 61, also a retired engineer. 
</P>
<P>
 The project will be financed by a $3.8-million loan from the California 
Housing Finance Agency, Schatzeder said. He expects construction to begin by 
June. 
</P>
<P>
 Of the proposed 51 rental units, 45 will be one-bedroom apartments, and six 
will have two bedrooms.  
</P>
<P>
 Hilda M. Veturis, the city's housing coordinator, said the project would cost 
the city $245,000, which include expenses to relocate tenants of the 12-unit 
apartment. 
</P>
<P>
 In addition, the city's Agency for Community Development has extended a 
$750,000, 30-year deferred loan to Schatzeder and his partner through the 
federal HOME program, Veturis said. The money will be used to pay for developer 
fees, traffic mitigation fees and other charges associated with construction, 
she said. 
</P>
<P>
 Veturis said that the loan will be forgiven if the developer agrees to set 
aside 11 units for single seniors with income not exceeding $20,600 a year and 
the remaining 40 units to seniors with annual incomes of no more than $27,000 a 
year. 
</P>
<P>
 The project will generate at least 50 construction jobs and allows the city to 
comply with state requirements to provide affordable housing to seniors, 
Veturis said.BERT ELJERA 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column; Brief 
</P>
</TYPE>
